      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat {{olive-oil}} of olive oil in a large saucepan over medium heat. Cook {{onion}} finely chopped onion for 8 minutes until soft. Add {{garlic}} of garlic, {{ginger-root}} of ginger, {{cumin-ground}} of ground cumin, {{coriander-ground}} of ground coriander, {{turmeric}} of ground turmeric, and {{chilli-flakes}} of chilli flakes; stir for 1 minute. Add {{apple-eating}} diced apple and stir for 2 minutes. Add {{red-lentils}} of rinsed red lentils and pour in {{stock-chicken}} of chicken stock. Season with {{sea-salt-fine}} of salt. Bring to the boil, reduce heat, and simmer for 20 minutes until the lentils are completely soft. Use a stick blender to blend about half the soup to thicken it while keeping some texture. Stir in {{coconut-milk}} of coconut milk and {{garam-masala}} of garam masala. Add the shredded chicken if using and warm through for 3 minutes. Squeeze in the lemon juice, taste for seasoning, and serve with coriander.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "intro": null,
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Add more stock and stir well. Only blend about half the soup, the texture should be thick but still have some body.",
              "cause": "Too many lentils for the quantity of stock, or blended too thoroughly.",
              "symptom": "Soup too thick, almost like porridge"
            },
            {
              "fix": "One eating apple per four portions is correct. Bramley (cooking apple) is too sharp here; use a Cox or similar eating apple.",
              "cause": "Apple variety too tart, or added too much.",
              "symptom": "Apple flavour overwhelms"
            },
            {
              "fix": "The spice paste needs at least 1 minute of frying in the oil. It should smell fragrant before the lentils and stock are added.",
              "cause": "Not cooked long enough in the oil before the liquid went in.",
              "symptom": "Spices taste raw"
            }
          ],
          "heading": "Common problems"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Mulligatawny is colonial cooking laid bare. British cooks in India tried to make a meat soup using local spices. The result belongs to neither tradition but has its own clear character. The soup came back to Britain with the colonial families. It became a Victorian and Edwardian favourite. Today it sits in British cooking as a warming winter soup.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
